# Token Efficiency

## Read Less, Search More

- Use `Grep` or `Glob` before reading full files. Only read the specific line ranges you need.
- Never re-read a file already shown in context or open in the IDE.
- For large files (>200 lines), read with `offset` and `limit` — never the whole file.

## Write Less

- Use `StrReplace` with minimal context (just enough to be unique). Never rewrite entire files.
- Never repeat unchanged code in edits. Only show the delta.
- Batch independent tool calls in a single message.

## Avoid Redundant Output

- Do not echo back code you just wrote. The user sees it in the diff.
- Keep explanations to 2-3 sentences unless the user asks for detail.
- Do not narrate each step ("First I'll read…", "Now I'll edit…"). Just do it.

## Leverage Cached Context

- Assume open/recently viewed files from IDE state are already in context — don't re-read them.
- Assume previous conversation turns are still in context — don't re-summarize prior work.
- When the user references a file with `@`, treat it as already loaded.
